				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">and why did I not need to do these weird bounds checking in my filter 0 encoder?</div><br />There's no accumulation involved with filter 0.<br /><br /><strong>Filter 0: new = sample</strong>, and <strong>sample = (nibble SHL shift) SAR 1</strong><br /><br />The nibbles are viewed as signed (range -8..+7), and the maximum allowed shift is 12. So the largest positive value you'd been able to produce with filter 0 is <strong>(7 SHL 12) SAR 1</strong> = 0x3800, which is in the safe range. <br /><br />For negative values the max would be <strong>(-8 SHL 12) SAR 1</strong> = 0xC000 = -0x4000 (16-bit), which when clipped to 15-bit should still be -0x4000. This would not be safe to use according to the fullsnes document, since it falls below -0x3FFA.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

